By product-to-sum,
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ} - 2 \sin 70^\circ &= \frac{1 - 4 \sin 10^\circ \sin 70^\circ}{2 \sin 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1 - 2 (\cos 60^\circ - \cos 80^\circ)}{2 \sin 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{2 \cos 80^\circ}{2 \sin 10^\circ} = \boxed{1}.
\end{align*}

Rotating $360^\circ$ is the same as doing nothing, so rotating $600^\circ$ is the same as rotating $600^\circ - 360^\circ = 240^\circ$.  Therefore, we have $\sin 600^\circ = \sin (600^\circ - 360^\circ) = \sin 240^\circ$.

