In general, the real part of a complex number $z$ is given by
\[\frac{z + \overline{z}}{2}.\]Hence, the real part of $1/z$ is equal to 1/6 if and only if
\[\frac{\frac{1}{z} + \frac{1}{\overline{z}}}{2} = \frac{1}{6},\]or
\[\frac{1}{z} + \frac{1}{\overline{z}} = \frac{1}{3}.\]Multiplying both sides by $3z \overline{z}$, we get
\[3z + 3 \overline{z} = z \overline{z}.\]We can re-write this equation as
\[z \overline{z} - 3z - 3 \overline{z} + 9 = 9.\]The left-hand side factors as
\[(z - 3)(\overline{z} - 3) = 9.\]Since $\overline{z} - 3$ is the conjugate of $z - 3$, this equation becomes
\[|z - 3|^2 = 9.\][asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

draw(Circle((3,0),3),red);
draw((-0.5,0)--(6.5,0));
draw((0,-3)--(0,3));
filldraw(Circle((0,0),0.1),white,red);

label("Re", (6.5,0), NE);
label("Im", (0,3), NE);
dot("$3$", (3,0), N);
[/asy]

Hence, $S$ is the set of complex numbers that have a distance of 3 from the complex number 3 (except 0).  This is a circle of radius 3, so the area of the region inside is $\boxed{9 \pi}$.

instruction:
The trapezoid shown has a height of length $12\text{ cm},$ a base of length $16\text{ cm},$ and an area of $162\text{ cm}^2.$ What is the perimeter of the trapezoid? [asy]
draw((0,0)--(0,12)--(11,12)--(16,0)--cycle);
label("12 cm",(-1,6),W);
draw((0.8,0)--(0.8,0.8)--(0,.8));
draw((0,11.2)--(0.8,11.2)--(0.8,12));
label("16 cm",(8,-1),S);
[/asy]

output:
We first label the trapezoid $ABCD$ as shown in the diagram below. Since $AD$ is the height of the trapezoid, then $AB$ and $DC$ are parallel. The area of the trapezoid is \begin{align*}
\frac{AD}{2}\times(AB+DC)&=\frac{12}{2}\times(AB+16) \\
&=6\times(AB+16).
\end{align*} Since the area of the trapezoid is $162,$  we have $6\times(AB+16)=162$ so that $$AB+16=\frac{162}{6}.$$ Solving for $AB$, we obtain $AB=11.$

Construct a perpendicular from $B$ to $E$ on $DC.$ Since $AB$ and $DE$ are parallel, and both $AD$ and $BE$ are perpendicular to $DE,$ we know that $ABED$ is a rectangle. Thus, $DE=AB=11,$ $BE=AD=12,$ and \begin{align*}
EC&=DC-DE \\
&=16-11 \\
&=5.
\end{align*} Since $\angle BEC=90^{\circ},$ we know that $\triangle BEC$ is a right triangle. Thus by the Pythagorean Theorem, \begin{align*}
BC^2&=BE^2+EC^2 \\
&= 12^2+5^2 \\
&= 169
\end{align*} so that $BC=13$ (since $BC>0$).

The perimeter of the trapezoid is $$AB+BC+CD+DA=11+13+16+12=\boxed{52}\text{ cm}.$$ [asy]
draw((0,0)--(0,12)--(11,12)--(16,0)--cycle);
draw((11,0)--(11,12),dashed);
draw((11.7,0)--(11.7,.7)--(11,.7));
label("$A$",(0,12),NW);
label("$B$",(11,12),NE);
label("$C$",(16,0),SE);
label("$E$",(11,0),S);
label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
label("12 cm",(-1,6),W);
label("16 cm",(8,-1),S);
[/asy]

The area of triangle $ABC$ is given by
\[[ABC] = \frac{1}{2} AC \cdot BC \cdot \sin C.\][asy]
unitsize (1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,0);
B = (5,0);
C = (1,2);
D = extension(C, incenter(A,B,C), A, B);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(C--D);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$6$", (C + D)/2, NE);
[/asy]

We can also write
\begin{align*}
[ABC] &= [ACD] + [BCD] \\
&= \frac{1}{2} AC \cdot CD \sin \frac{C}{2} + \frac{1}{2} BC \cdot CD \sin \frac{C}{2} \\
&= 3AC \sin \frac{C}{2} + 3BC \sin \frac{C}{2} \\
&= 3 (AC + BC) \sin \frac{C}{2}.
\end{align*}Thus,
\[\frac{1}{2} AC \cdot BC \cdot \sin C = 3(AC + BC) \sin \frac{C}{2}.\]Then
\[AC \cdot BC \sin \frac{C}{2} \cos \frac{C}{2} = 3(AC + BC) \sin \frac{C}{2},\]so
\[\frac{AC \cdot BC}{3} = 3 (AC + BC).\]Hence,
\[\frac{1}{AC} + \frac{1}{BC} = \frac{AC + BC}{AC \cdot BC} = \boxed{\frac{1}{9}}.\]

The $y$-intercept is $(0,c).$  Since this is the point closest to $(12,3),$ the line joining $(0,c)$ and $(12,3)$ is perpendicular to the tangent to the parabola at $(0,c).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

real parab (real x) {
  return(x^2 + 6*x + 5);
}

draw(graph(parab,-6.5,0.5),red);
draw((-7,0)--(15,0));
draw((0,-5)--(0,10));
draw(((0,5) + (5)*(1/6,1))--((0,5) + (-8)*(1/6,1)),dashed);
draw((0,5)--(12,3));

dot("$(12,3)$", (12,3), E);
dot("$(-5,0)$", (-5,0), SW);
dot("$(0,c)$", (0,5), W);
[/asy]

The equation of the tangent is of the form
\[y - c = mx\]for some real number $m,$ so $y = mx + c.$  Substituting into $y = x^2 + bx + c,$ we get
\[mx + c = x^2 + bx + c,\]so $x^2 + (b - m) x = 0.$  Since $y = mx + c$ is the equation of the tangent at $x = 0,$ this quadratic should have a double root of $x = 0,$ which means $m = b.$

Thus, the slope of the tangent is $b.$  The slope of the line joining $(0,c)$ and $(12,3)$ is $\frac{3 - c}{12},$ so
\[b \cdot \frac{3 - c}{12} = -1.\]Then $b = -\frac{12}{3 - c} = \frac{12}{c - 3}.$

Also, the parabola passes through $(-5,0),$ so
\[0 = 25 - 5b + c.\]Substituting $b = \frac{12}{c - 3},$ we get
\[25 - \frac{60}{c - 3} + c = 0.\]This simplifies to $c^2 + 22c - 135 = 0,$ which factors as $(c - 5)(c + 27) = 0.$  Hence, $c = 5$ or $c = -27.$

If $c = -27,$ then $b = -\frac{2}{5},$ which does not satisfy the given conditions.  Therefore, $c = 5,$ and $b = 6,$ so $(b,c) = \boxed{(6,5)}.$

We have that
\begin{align*}
\frac{1 - \cos \theta}{\sin \theta} - \frac{\sin \theta}{1 + \cos \theta} &= \frac{(1 - \cos \theta)(1 + \cos \theta) - \sin^2 \theta}{\sin \theta (1 + \cos \theta)} \\
&= \frac{1 - \cos^2 \theta - \sin^2 \theta}{\sin \theta (1 + \cos \theta)} \\
&= \boxed{0}.
\end{align*}

